revision.text:
{{Infobox book | name = Archive Fever: A Freudian Impression | title_orig = Mal d'Archive: Une Impression Freudienne | translator = | image = File:Archive Fever, French edition.gif | caption = Cover of the first edition | author = [[Jacques Derrida]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = France | language = French | series = | subject = [[Archive|The Archive]] | publisher = [[Éditions Galilée]] | release_date = 1995 | english_release_date = 1996 | media_type = Print | pages = | isbn = | dewey= | congress= | oclc= | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''Archive Fever: A Freudian Impression''''' ({{lang-fr|Mal d'Archive: Une Impression Freudienne}}) is a book by the French philosopher [[Jacques Derrida]] first published in 1995 by [[Éditions Galilée]]. An English translation by Eric Prenowitz was published in 1996.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Veryard|first1=Richard|title=Review of "Jacques Derrida. Archive Fever: A Freudian Impression"|url=http://www.users.globalnet.co.uk/~rxv/infomgt/archive.htm|website=Richard Veryard|publisher=Veryard Projects|accessdate=17 April 2017}}</ref>
==Summary== In ''Archive Fever'', Derrida discusses the nature and function of the [[archive]], particularly in [[Sigmund Freud|Freudian]] terms and in light of the [[death drive]]. The book also contains discussions of [[Judaism]] and [[Jewish identity]] and of electronic technology such as [[e-mail]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sampson|first1=Walker|title=From My Archives: Derrida’s Archive Fever|url=https://wsampson.wordpress.com/2011/04/10/from-my-archives-derridas-archive-fever/|website=Walker Sampson|accessdate=17 April 2017}}</ref>
