The '''[[Bratislava]] Declaration''' was the result of the conference held on 3 August 1968 for the representatives of the Communist parties and Worker's parties of [[People's Republic of Bulgaria|Bulgaria]], [[Hungarian People's Republic|Hungary]], [[East Germany]], [[Polish People's Republic|Poland]], the [[Union of Soviet Socialist Republics|USSR]], and [[Czechoslovakia]].<ref name="bratislava declaration august 3rd">{{cite web|url=http://library.thinkquest.org/C001155/documents/doc41.htm|accessdate=4 April 2014|title=The Bratislava Declaration, August 3, 1968}}</ref> The declaration was a response to the [[Prague Spring]]. It affirmed unshakable fidelity to Marxism–Leninism and proletarian internationalism, and declared an implacable struggle against "bourgeois" ideology and all "anti-socialist" forces. The Soviet Union also expressed its intention to intervene in any [[Warsaw Pact]] country if a "bourgeois" system – a pluralist system of several political parties – was ever established.<ref name="ussr czechoslovakia intervention">{{cite web|url=http://www.onwar.com/aced/data/cite/czechoslovak1968.htm|accessdate=12 October 2014|title=USSR Czechoslovakia Intervention 1968}}</ref>

The [[Bratislava Declaration and Roadmap]] is an unrelated document that was the outcome of an informal meeting of the 27 heads of state or government on September 16, 2016, chaired by [[Donald Tusk]].<ref>[http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2016/09/16-bratislava-declaration-and-roadmap/ "...devoted to diagnose together the present state of the European Union and discuss our common future..."]</ref>

