{{Infobox ancient site | name = Nwya Devu | native_name = | alternate_name = 尼阿底遗址 | image = | image_size = 250px | alt = | caption = | map_type = Tibet#China | map_alt = Location in Tibet | map_caption = Location in Tibet | map_size = 250px | altitude_m = 4600 | altitude_ref = {{sfn|Zhang|Ha|Wang|Chen|2018|p=1049}} | relief = yes | coordinates = {{coord|31|28|N|88|48|E|display=inline,title}}{{sfn|Zhang|Ha|Wang|Chen|2018|p=3 (Supplementary)}} | location = [[Xainza County]], Nagqu, Tibet Autonomous Region, China{{sfn|Zhang|Ha|Wang|Chen|2018|p=3 (Supplementary)}} | region = eastern [[Changtang]]{{sfn|Zhang|Ha|Wang|Chen|2018|p=3 (Supplementary)}} | type = open-air site | part_of = | length = | width = | area = | height = | builder = | material = | built = | abandoned = | epochs = | cultures = | dependency_of = | occupants = | event = | excavations = 2013, 2016-2018 | archaeologists = | condition = | ownership = | management = | public_access = | website = | notes = }} '''Nwya Devu''' is a high-altitude archaeological site on the [[Tibetan Plateau]] located in the eastern [[Changtang]] region of Tibet. At around {{convert|4600|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} above sea level, Nwya Devu is the highest known archaeological site from the [[Paleolithic]] and provides evidence for the earliest known presence of humans at a high-altitude site, at around 40,000-30,000 [[Before Present|BP]].{{sfn|Zhang|Ha|Wang|Chen|2018|p=1049}}
==Background== The site was discovered in 2013 during [[Systematic survey|systematic archaeological surveying]] performed by the Tibetan Cultural Relics Conservation Institute and the [[Institute of Vertebrate Paleontology and Paleoanthropology]].{{sfn|Zhang|Ha|Wang|Chen|2018|p=3 (Supplementary)}} Nywa Devu lies on the former [[Terrace (geology)#Lacustrine_terraces|lacrustrine terrace]] of Co Ngoin, a nearby freshwater lake to the site's north.{{sfn|Zhang|Ha|Wang|Chen|2018|p=4 (Supplementary)}}
==Stratigraphy== Archaeologists identified three [[Stratigraphy (archaeology)|stratigraphic]] layers at the site and excavated around {{convert|170|cm|ft|0|abbr=on}} worth of deposits in depth.{{sfn|Zhang|Ha|Wang|Chen|2018|p=1049}} Layer 1 is [[Luminescence dating|OSL dated]] from around 13,000 to 4,000 [[Before Present|BP]]. Mollusc shells taken from the lowest part of Layer 1 yielded [[Radiocarbon dating#Accelerator mass spectrometry|AMS date]] ranges from around 12,700 to 12,400 BP, which shows concurrence with the OSL dating. Layer 2 is OSL dated from around 25,000 to 18,000 BP and corresponds with the [[Last Glacial Maximum]]. The earliest layer, Layer 3, is OSL dated to around 45,000 to 30,000 BP.{{sfn|Zhang|Ha|Wang|Chen|2018|p=1050}} While artefacts were found outside of Layer 3, the archaeologists who worked the site believe that all of the artefacts come from the assemblage associated with Layer 3.{{sfn|Zhang|Ha|Wang|Chen|2018|pp=1049-1050}}{{sfn|Zhang|Dennell|2018}} Paleo-environmental evidence suggests that the local climate was milder during the time of Layer 3 when compared against the present.{{sfn|Zhang|Dennell|2018}}
==Artefacts== 3,683 lithic artefacts were excavated from the site. The lithic assemblage at Nwya Devu consists primarily of blade cores, flake cores, blades, flakes, chunks, and tools. All of the lithic artefacts at Newa Devu were sourced from black [[slate]] that was locally derived, from nearby Nwya Devu Hill, which lies around {{convert|800|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} east of the site. Blades found at the site were made using a non-[[Levallois technique]], through the use of prismatic cores.{{sfn|Zhang|Ha|Wang|Chen|2018|p=1050}} Archaeologists believe that Nwya Devu, with access to a good source of raw materials nearby, was likely the site of a lithic tool-making workshop, with a primary focus on creating long knives and scrapers that could be [[Hafting|hafted]].{{sfn|Zhang|Dennell|2018}} Some of the excavated blades were over {{convert|20|cm|in|0|abbr=on}} in length.{{sfn|Zhang|Dennell|2018}} The lithic assemblage at Newa Dwvu appears to be unique and not obviously related to any other sites in East Asia.{{sfn|Zhang|Dennell|2018}} It shows some similarities to sites from the Early [[Upper Paleolithic]] in Siberia (Kara Bom) and Mongolia (Tolbor-21).{{sfn|Zhang|Ha|Wang|Chen|2018|p=1051}}{{sfn|Zhang|Ha|Wang|Chen|2018|p=4 (Supplementary)}}
