{{Infobox journal | title = Programming Historian | cover = Programming_Historian_(English).png | abbreviation = | formernames = Programming Historian 2 | discipline = [[History]] | editor = Anandi Silva Knuppel | publisher = Editorial Board of the Programming Historian | country = International | history = 2012-present | frequency = Ongoing Integrating | impact = | impact-year = | website = https://programminghistorian.org/ | ISSN = 2397-2068 | eISSN = | JSTOR = | OCLC = | LCCN = | CODEN =
}}
The '''''Programming Historian''''' is a [[peer-reviewed]] [[academic journal]] of [[digital humanities]] and [[digital history]] methodology.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Review: The Programming Historian|url = https://doi.org/10.1093/jahist/jaw172|journal = Journal of American History|date = 2016-06-01|pages = 299-301|volume = 103|issue = 1|first = Jeff|last = McClurken}}</ref> It publishes tutorials that help humanists learn a wide range of digital tools, techniques, and workflows to facilitate research and teaching.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Review of The Programming Historian|url = https://jitp.commons.gc.cuny.edu/review-of-the-programming-historian/|journal = The Journal of Interactive Technology & Pedagogy|date = 2015-12-15|first = Cameron|last = Blevins}}</ref> It was based upon an original series of lessons written by William J. Turkel and Alan MacEachern of the [[University of Western Ontario]] in 2008.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = The Programming Historian|url = https://ir.lib.uwo.ca/historydig/3/|journal = Scholarship @ Western|date = 2008|first = William|last = J. Turkel|first2 = Alan|last2 = MacEachern}}</ref> The project launched as an academic journal in 2012 at the Digital Humanities 2012 conference in [[Hamburg]].<ref name="Digital Humanities 2012: The Programming Historian 2">{{cite web |url=http://www.dh2012.uni-hamburg.de/conference/programme/abstracts/the-programming-historian-2-a-participatory-textbook.1.html |title=The Programming Historian 2: Digital Humanities 2012 |accessdate=2018-05-23}}</ref>
The journal publishes tutorials in [[English language|English]] or [[Spanish language|Spanish]]. It operates with an open peer review model, and all content is released under a [[Creative Commons]] CC-BY license, meaning it meets the criteria of Green [[Open Access]] publishing.
The project has twice won a "Digital Humanities Award". In 2016 it won "Best Series of Posts" for its English-language content.<ref name="Digital Humanities Awards 2016">{{cite web |url=http://dhawards.org/dhawards2016/results/ |title=Digital Humanities Awards 2016 |accessdate=2018-05-23}}</ref> In 2017 it won "Best Series of Posts" for its Spanish-language content.<ref name="Digital Humanities Awards 2017">{{cite web |url=http://dhawards.org/dhawards2017/results/ |title=Digital Humanities Awards 2017 |accessdate=2018-05-23}}</ref> The project has also been involved in social issues in digital humanities, conducting a self-reflection and survey into gender biases in the project in 2015 in an attempt to encourage more participation from female authors and reviewers.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Identifying and Removing Gender Barriers in Open Learning Communities|url = https://www.herts.ac.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0016/138013/Blip-2016-Autumn-2016-Final-Autumn-2016.pdf|journal = Blended Learning in Practice|date = 2016|pages = 49-61|volume = 11|first = Adam|last = Crymble}}</ref>
It is indexed by the [[Directory of Open Access Journals]].<ref name="Directory of Open Access Journals">{{cite web |url=https://doaj.org/toc/2397-2068 |title="Programming Historian", Directory of Open Access Journals |accessdate=2018-05-23}}</ref> It is also listed among proprietary databases and other e-resources at Harvard University Library.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Review: Historian, Program! Self-Help for Digital Neophytes|url = https://www.historians.org/publications-and-directories/perspectives-on-history/may-2017/historian-program-self-help-digital-neophytes|journal = Perspectives in History: The Newsmagazine of the American Historical Association |date = 2017|first = Seth|last = Denbo|accessdate=2018-06-01}}</ref>
