'''Utu'''{{efn|[[Akkadian (language)|Akkadian]] rendition<ref>http://www.sumerian.org/sumlogo.htm s.v. "babbar(2)"</ref><ref>Frederick Augustus Vanderbergh : ''Sumerian Hymns from Cuneiform Texts in the British Museum''. Columbia University Press, 1908. [https://books.google.com/books?id=lk0YAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA53&lpg=PA53&dq=Sumerian+UD+sun&source=bl&ots=ew7v7u-uGk&sig=ZZ9xA87ULWnNIWlwlpk8ssRn6bY&hl=en&ei=NbXhSq6ALsHj8QaO6ejyAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CA0Q6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Sumerian%20UD%20sun&f=false p. 53].</ref> of [[Sumerian language|Sumerian]] <sup>d</sup>UD 𒀭𒌓 "[[Sun]]",<ref>{{cite journal| url=http://www.folklore.ee/Folklore/vol16/planets.pdf |author1=Kasak, Enn |author2=Veede, Raul |title=Understanding Planets in Ancient Mesopotamia (PDF) |journal = Electronic Journal of Folklore |issn = 1406-0957 |volume=16 |year = 2001 |pages = 7&ndash;35 |publisher  = Estonian Literary Museum |editor1=Mare Kõiva |editor2=Andres Kuperjanov |doi=10.7592/fejf2001.16.planets}}
The [[Sumerian cuneiform]] character is encoded in [[Unicode]] at U+12313 𒌓 (Borger nr. 381). Borger's 381 is U4.  http://www.sron.nl/~jheise/signlists/top20.html</ref>}} later worshipped by [[East Semitic]] peoples as '''Shamash''',{{efn|Akkadian ''šamaš'' "Sun" is [[cognate]] to {{lang-phn|𐤔𐤌𐤔}} ''šmš'', {{lang-syc|ܫܡܫܐ}} ''šemša'', {{lang-he|שֶׁמֶשׁ}} ''šemeš'' and {{lang-ar|شمس}} ''šams''.}} is the [[List of Mesopotamian deities|ancient Mesopotamian]] [[Sun god|god of the sun]], justice, morality, and truth, and the twin brother of the goddess [[Inanna]], the [[Queen of heaven (antiquity)|Queen of Heaven]]. His main temples were in the cities of [[Sippar]] and [[Larsa]]. He was believed to ride through the heavens in his [[sun chariot]] and see all things that happened in the day. He was the enforcer of [[Divine judgment|divine justice]] and was thought to aid those in distress. According to Sumerian mythology, he helped protect [[Dumuzid]] when the ''[[gallu|galla]]'' demons tried to drag him to the Underworld and he appeared to the hero [[Ziusudra]] after the [[Flood myth|Great Flood]]. In the ''[[Epic of Gilgamesh]]'', he helps [[Gilgamesh]] defeat the ogre [[Humbaba]].

==Family==
Utu was the twin brother of Inanna,{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=182}}{{sfn|Pryke|2017|page=36}} the Queen of Heaven, whose domain encompassed a broad variety of different powers.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|pages=108–109}}{{sfn|Pryke|2017|page=36}} In Sumerian texts, Inanna and Utu are shown as extremely close;{{sfn|Pryke|2017|pages=36–37}} in fact, their relationship frequently borders on [[incest]]uous.{{sfn|Pryke|2017|pages=36–37}}{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=183}} Utu is usually the son of [[Sin (mythology)|Nanna]], the god of the moon, and his wife, [[Ningal]],{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|pages=182–184}}{{sfn|Mark|2017}} but is sometimes also described as the son of [[Anu|An]] or [[Enlil]].{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|pages=182–184}}{{sfn|Mark|2017}} His wife was the goddess [[Sherida]], later known in Akkadian as Aya.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=184}}{{sfn|Holland|2009|page=115}}{{sfn|Mark|2017}} Sherida was a goddess of beauty, fertility, and sexual love,{{sfn|Holland|2009|page=115}} possibly because light was seen as inherently beautiful, or because of the sun's role in promoting agricultural fertility.{{sfn|Holland|2009|page=115}} They were believed to have two offspring: the goddess Kittu, whose name means "Truth", and the god Misharu, whose name means "Justice".{{sfn|Holland|2009|page=115}} By the time of the [[First Babylonian dynasty|Old Babylonian Period]] ({{circa}} 1830 – {{circa}} 1531 BC), Sherida, and consequently Utu, was associated with ''[[nadītu]]'', an order of [[cloister]]ed women who devoted their lives to the gods.{{sfn|Mark|2017}} Utu's charioteer Bunene is sometimes described as his son.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=184}}{{sfn|Mark|2017}} Bunene was worshipped independently from Utu as a god of justice in [[Sippar]] and [[Uruk]] during the Old Babylonian Period{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=184}}{{sfn|Mark|2017}} and, in later times, he was also worshipped at [[Assur]].{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=184}}{{sfn|Mark|2017}}

==Worship==
Utu was worshipped in Sumer from the very earliest times.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=184}} The oldest documents mentioning him date to around 3500 BC, during the first stages of Sumerian writing.{{sfn|Mark|2017}} His main temples, which were both known as E-babbar ("White House"), were located in [[Sippar]] and in [[Larsa]].{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=184}} Utu continued to be venerated until the end of Mesopotamian culture{{sfn|Mark|2017}} and was worshipped for well over 3,000 years.{{sfn|Mark|2017}} Utu's main personality characteristics are his kindness and generosity,{{sfn|Mark|2017}} but, like all other Mesopotamian deities, he was not above refusing a request which inconvenienced him.{{sfn|Mark|2017}} In the [[Hurrian language|Hurro]]-Akkadian bilingual Weidner god list, Utu is equated with the [[Hurrians|Hurrian]] sun-god Šimigi.{{sfn|Simons|2017|page=83}} In the [[Ugarit]]ic trilingual version of the Weidner god list, Šimigi and Utu are both equated with [[Lugalbanda]].{{sfn|Simons|2017|page=86}}

==Iconography==
In Sumerian texts, Utu is described as "bearded" and "long-armed".{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=184}} In art, he is shown as an old man with a long beard.{{sfn|Mark|2017}} He was believed to emerge from the doors of [[Heaven]] every day at dawn and ride across the sky in his [[Sun chariot|chariot]] before returning to the "interior of heaven" through a set of doors in the far west every evening.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=184}} Utu's charioteer was named Bunene.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=52}} [[Cylinder seal]]s often show two gods holding the doors open for him as he wields his weapon, the pruning-saw,{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=184}} a double-edged arch-shaped saw with large, jagged teeth, representing his role as the god of justice.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=184}} Utu's main symbol was the solar disc,{{sfn|Mark|2017}} a circle with four points in each of the cardinal directions and four wavy, diagonal lines emanating from the circle between each point.{{sfn|Mark|2017}} This symbol represented the light, warmth, and power of the sun.{{sfn|Mark|2017}}

