==Mythology==
The Sumerians believed that, as he rode through heaven, Utu saw everything that happened in the world.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=184}}{{sfn|Holland|2009|page=115}} Alongside his sister Inanna, Utu was the enforcer of [[Divine judgement|divine justice]].{{sfn|Pryke|2017|pages=36–37}} At night, Utu was believed to travel through the Underworld as he journeyed to the east in preparation for the sunrise.{{sfn|Holland|2009|page=115}} One Sumerian literary work refers to Utu illuminating the Underworld and dispensing judgement there{{sfn|Horowitz|1998|page=352}} and Shamash Hymn 31 (BWL 126) states that Utu serves as a judge of the dead in the Underworld alongside the ''malku'', ''kusu'', and the [[Anunnaki]].{{sfn|Horowitz|1998|page=352}} On his way through the Underworld, Utu was believed to pass through the garden of the sun-god,{{sfn|Holland|2009|page=115}} which contained trees that bore precious gems as fruit.{{sfn|Holland|2009|page=115}}

Utu was believed to take an active role in human affairs,{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=184}} and was thought to aid those in distress.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=184}} In one of his earliest appearances in literature, in the ''Myth of Etana'', written before the conquest of [[Sargon of Akkad]] ({{circa}} 2334–2284 BC), the hero [[Etana]] invokes Utu to help his wife conceive a child.{{sfn|Mark|2017}} In the Sumerian poem ''The Dream of Dumuzid'', Utu intervenes to rescue Inanna's husband [[Dumuzid the Shepherd|Dumuzid]] from the ''[[gallu|galla]]'' demons who are hunting him.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=184}} In the Sumerian [[flood myth]], Utu emerges after the flood waters begin to subside,{{snf|Kramer|1961|page=98}}{{sfn|Hämmerly-Dupuy|1988|page=56}} causing [[Ziusudra]], the hero of the story, to throw open a window on his boat and fall down prostrate before him.{{snf|Kramer|1961|page=98}}{{sfn|Hämmerly-Dupuy|1988|page=56}} Ziusudra sacrifices a sheep and an ox to Utu for delivering him to salvation.{{snf|Kramer|1961|page=98}}{{sfn|Hämmerly-Dupuy|1988|page=56}}

In the [[Sumerian King List]], one of the early kings of [[Uruk]] is described as "the son of Utu"{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=184}} and Utu seems to have served as a special protector to several of that city's later kings.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=184}} In the Sumerian poem of ''Gilgamesh and Huwawa'', the hero [[Gilgamesh]] asks Utu to assist him in his journey to the [[Cedar Forest|Cedar Mountain]].{{sfn|Tigay|2002|page=76}} In this version, Gilgamesh asks Utu's help because Utu is associated with the Cedar Mountain, which is implied to be located in the far east, the land where the sun rises.{{sfn|Tigay|2002|pages=76–77}} Utu is initially reluctant to help,{{sfn|Tigay|2002|page=77}} but, after Gilgamesh explains that he is doing this because he intends to establish his name, because he knows he will eventually die, Utu agrees.{{sfn|Tigay|2002|pages=76–77}} Once Gilgamesh reaches the Cedar Mountain, Utu helps him defeat the ogre [[Humbaba|Huwawa]], who lives there.{{sfn|Tigay|2002|page=77}}

In the standard [[Babylonia]]n ''[[Epic of Gilgamesh]]'', Gilgamesh's plan to visit the Cedar Mountain is still his own idea and he goes to Shamash for aid.{{sfn|Tigay|2002|pages=77–78}} In this version, however, the Cedar Mountain is explicitly stated to be located in the northwest, in [[Lebanon]].{{sfn|Tigay|2002|page=78}} Shamash helps Gilgamesh defeat [[Humbaba]] (the East Semitic name for Huwawa).{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=184}}{{sfn|Tigay|2002|pages=77–81}} Jeffrey H. Tigay suggests that Lugalbanda's association with the sun-god in the [[First Babylonian Dynasty|Old Babylonian]] version of the epic strengthened "the impression that at one point in the history of the tradition the sun-god was also invoked as an ancestor".{{sfn|Tigay|2002|pages=76–81}} In the Sumerian version, Gilgamesh's initial quest is to visit the Cedar Mountain and Humbaba is merely an obstacle that Gilgamesh and Enkidu encounter once they have already arrived there,{{sfn|Tigay|2002|pages=77, 79}} but, in the Babylonian version, defeating Humbaba is the initial quest on which the heroes embark.{{sfn|Tigay|2002|page=79}} In a late version of the Gilgamesh story, Shamash becomes the instigator of the quest, the one who instructs Gilgamesh to go slay Humbaba to begin with.{{sfn|Tigay|2002|page=79}} Tigay describes this as the "final and logical development of [Shamash's] role."{{sfn|Tigay|2002|page=79}}

==Later influence==
The authors of the [[Hebrew Bible]] generally attempt to portray the sun in a non-anthropomorphic manner, sometimes using it as a symbol of [[Yahweh]]'s power.{{sfn|van der Toorn|Becking|van der Horst|1999|page=960}} The Hebrew word for "sun", ''šapaš'' or ''šemeš'', is often substituted for euphemisms, such as the word ''or'', meaning "light".{{sfn|van der Toorn|Becking|van der Horst|1999|page=960}} These authors appear to have made a conscious effort to avoid implications of sun worship, even of a Yahwistic variety, at all costs.{{sfn|van der Toorn|Becking|van der Horst|1999|page=960}} However, the [[Woman of the Apocalypse]] in the [[Book of Revelation]], may directly allude to ancient Near Eastern sun goddesses.{{sfn|van der Toorn|Becking|van der Horst|1999|page=960}}

